ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: ACAD.CATEGORY.CERT
PURPOSE: List of academic levels from OTHER.ACAD.LEVELS code file, to say what academic level this credential certifies, this person to teach.  Used to determine if this person, can teach a course section.  If entered, one of the, values in this field has to match the academic level of, the course section, or else the faculty member should not, be assigned to the section.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: ACAD.COURSE.CERT
PURPOSE: The location at which the associated course, may be taught.  Used when assigning faculty, to a course section; if the location of the, section does not match this location for the, associated course during the specified dates,, a warning will be issued.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: ACAD.COURSE.CERT
PURPOSE: List of courses this credential certifies this, person to teach.  If there are any entries here,, the faculty member can only be assigned to course, sections that correspond to one of these entries., The faculty member can also teach a cross-listed, version of the course; for example, if one entry, is ENGL100, and ENGL100 is cross listed as LIT110,, then the faculty member can be assigned to LIT110, as well., , Note that if courses are entered, those override, anything else entered for a faculty certification, for the dates of the certification.  The only, location used in conjunction with the course is, the one in the course group., , For example, if a person can teach ENGL100 at, location WEST from 1/1/96 - 5/5/96, then only, ENGL100 sections at location WEST active during, those dates should be assigned to the faculty, member during those dates.  If, however, the, person is also qualified to teach 100-level, courses for dates outside that range, then a, course level 100 can be entered.  This would, mean the faculty member will be qualified to, teach any 100-level course outside the date range., (The course level qualifications would be entered, on the ST FQAL/FIS007 screen.)

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: ACAD.CATEGORY.CERT
PURPOSE: List of departments used to determine if this, person can teach a course section in the associated, academic level.  If this field is to be used as, criteria for qualification checking, the department, and the associated academic level must match the, academic level and one of the departments in the, course section, or else the faculty member should, not be assigned to the section., , If a subject is also in the association, all, 3 (academic level, department, subject) must match, what is in the course section before the faculty, member should be assigned to that section.
This code signifies where the person is eligible to, be employed.  Used in Wisconsin state reporting,, but not otherwise used by the system.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: ACAD.CERT.NEEDED
PURPOSE: This is a code that can be used to specify any action, that needs to be taken on the associated certification, requirement.  It can denote a reporting action, such, as add or delete, to know what to send to the state,, or can be an action that needs to be taken by the person, trying to achieve another level of the credential.  It, is only used by the system for Wisconsin state reporting,, where the values say how to report the associated requirement.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: ACAD.CERT.NEEDED
PURPOSE: This is the list of requirements that are either, needed for renewal of the certification, or that are, needed to move to a higher level of certification., Used in Wisconsin state reporting, but not otherwise, used by the system.

This field specifies whether or not the certification, restricts the person to participating in a part-time, role or on some other basis., , Used in Wisconsin state reporting, but not used within, base Colleague.

Sometimes a person whose credential only allows part, time participation will be allowed to participate in a, full time role.  If this is the case, this override, flag can be set to Yes to show that although the, certification implies only part time, the person can, be involved in a full time capacity., , Used in Wisconsin state reporting, but not otherwise, used by the system.

Yes/no flag saying if the staff member has requested, certification.  Yes means the staff member requested it,, No means it was requested by some person or agency, other than the person.  Used in Wisconsin state, reporting, but not otherwise used by the system.

This code reflects the status of the certification., It is kept in order to report if a certification which is, to be deleted has been previously reported.  It is used in, Wisconsin state reporting, but not otherwise used by the, system.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: ACAD.CATEGORY.CERT
PURPOSE: List of subjects used to determine if this, person can teach a course section in the associated, academic level.  If this field is to be used as, criteria for qualification checking, the subject, and the associated academic level must match the, academic level and the subject of the course, section, or else the faculty member should not be, assigned to the section., , If a department is also in the association, all, 3 (academic level, department, subject) must match, what is in the course section before the faculty, member should be assigned to that section.

This field will be calculated when the record is created.  Its purpose is to , provide an index that can be used to determine quickly whether a record already , exists with the specified text, since even a small change to the text would , result in a different hash value. ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: CLRM.CONTACTS
PURPOSE: The ID of the person who is associated to the role, for the room.  Can be used to know who to get in, touch with if a question arises.  Maintained but not, otherwise used by the system.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: CLRM.CONTACTS
PURPOSE: The contact type of a person in this room.  This, can be used to note people at a room that can be, reached for questions about admissions, scheduling,, etc.  It is maintained but not otherwise used by the, system.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: EQUIP
PURPOSE: This is the list of equipment codes for the equipment, available in the room.  It is used to match the, equipment codes required by a course section to the, equipment codes in the room to see if the room is, suitable for the course., , If asset IDs have been entered in this room, the, asset type is checked to see if it has an equipment, code.  If so, the equipment code is added to this, list and a quantity of one is put into the quantity., The quantity can then be changed as needed.  This, avoids double entry of an asset ID and an equipment, code.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: EQUIP
PURPOSE: This is the number of like items in the room., , If fixed assets is installed and asset IDs have, been entered, this number will be calculated based, on the equipment code associated to the asset type, on FXP006.  If this number is manually entered,, the notation of "(Manual)" will appear next to, the quantity to show that the quantity is no, longer related to the assets shown.  If there, are no assets, the manual designation does not, display., , This quantity is used along with the equipment, code by the Student (ST) application when a course, section is to be assigned to a room.  If the, section requires certain equipment, the equipment, code on the section is checked against the, equipment code on the room to see if the equipment, is available in the room.  Then the section equipment, quantity is checked against this quantity to see if, there is enough of the equipment.  A warning is, issued if there is no equipment of the type required, or if there is insufficient equipment.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: EQUIP
PURPOSE: Yes/no flag specifying if the equipment quantity was, calculated by the system or manually entered.  No, means the quantity was calculated by the system.  Yes, means an alternate quantity was entered.  This field, is system-maintained and not meant to be modified by, the user.  It is provided as a visual cue that the, quantity entered does not add up to the asset IDs, entered for the room.

These are the list of academic levels for which this, special day is valid.  It can be used to print the, calendar by academic level.  It is used by the system, when scheduling an event with an academic level to see, if this special day applies.  If this field is left, blank, this applies to all academic levels., , For example, if a course section is being scheduled, and this field is not blank, then the academic level, of the course section is checked against the academic, levels in this field.  If there is a match, and a, course section is not in the event types excluded list,, then the section is NOT scheduled for this day.

The list of event types that are excluded from, considering this a holiday., , All special days in this file are created with, an event type of holiday.  This means that normally,, nothing is to be scheduled on this day.  For example,, if November 22 is set up as Thanksgiving, then no, classes, buildings, rooms, etc., are normally booked, on that day, and the day is skipped when a schedule, is being built for something or someone that spans, November 22., , However, some special days are to have some activities, scheduled but not others.  For instance, a flex day, may have faculty office hours scheduled, but not, course sections.  In this case, faculty office hours, (the event type with the special processing code of FI), would be entered in this field so that this day would be, a normally scheduled day for faculty office hours.

This is the relative priority of a department for use, in scheduling rooms via SCHEDULE25.  It is a one-digit, number with 1 being the lowest priority to 9 being the, highest priority. It cannot be zero or left blank.,  , This conflict decider is only used if more than one, department ends up trying to get the same room at the, same time on the same day, which would be a fairly rare, occurrence since SCHEDULE25 tries to balance rooms as, much as possible.  To resolve the conflict, this number is, used to see which department takes precedence.  If both, departments happen to have the same conflict decider value,, SCHEDULE25 will just pick one of the departments.

This is the institution with which this department is, associated.  This is used for places that have one, Colleague database, but need to report multiple, FICE codes., , This does NOT imply that this release of Colleague, is a multi-institution system.  This simply allows, a consortium of multiple FICE codes to list the, FICE (or any other) code from the INSTITUTIONS file, on reports., , If this department has an associated division or, school, the institution code may be entered there, instead.  Colleague looks at department first,, since most transactions in the Colleague applications, other than Core can be traced back to a department., If no institution exists for the department, then , Colleague checks if a division or school is associated, with the department.  If so, it checks the division or, school for an institution ID.  If a division was being, checked, and there is no institution for the division,, but the division is associated to a school, then the, school is checked for an institution ID.  If no, institution ID is found anywhere, the ID entered on, the PID2 (ID and LookUp Parameters) screen in the, Host Organization ID field is used.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: DEPTS.PARTITIONS
PURPOSE: This is the group of the department's preferred partition., Schedule 25 allows 4 groupings of partitions to, prioritize the order in which a partition will be used, to have its rooms assigned for a department.  The lower, the group number, the higher the priority.  For example,, partitions in group 1 will be used first, then partitions, in group 2, etc., , In Schedule 25, these are referred to as "clusters".

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: DEPTS.PARTITIONS
PURPOSE: This is a list of the partitions a department would prefer in, scheduling rooms for its course sections using Schedule 25. If, partitions are entered here, Schedule 25 will attempt to use the, rooms in these partitions when assigning rooms to the course, sections of this department.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: DUPL.FIELD.RATINGS
PURPOSE: The name of the field to be compared to.  These are, fields in the Colleague database against which the, intermediate file field will be compared., , If this field is multi-valued and the field in, ELFDUPL.FIELDS is single-valued, then if the value, in ELFDUPL.FIELDS matches any occurrence of the, values in this ELFDUPL.COMPARE.TO.FIELDS, that is, considered a duplicate and will be given the, associated weight or penalty.
A description of the duplicate criteria.  Displayed on, resolution screens.

An integer used to determine if records in two files, are duplicates., , When a record is evaluated to see if it is a duplicate,, the weights are added together when the values in the, associated fields are the same between two records., The penalties are subtracted when the values in the, associated fields are different between the two records., The sum of the weights, minus the penalties, is then, compared to this duplicate rating number.  If the sum, is greater than or equal to the duplicate rating,, the record is considered a duplicate of an existing, record; if the sum is less than the duplicate rating, but greater than or equal to the possible duplicate, rating, the record is considered to be a possible, duplicate of an existing record., , For example, suppose that the duplicate rating is 15,, that a field called SSN has a weight of 10, and, that a field called LAST.NAME has a weight of 10., If file A is being compared to file B, and file A, has a record whose SSN matches the SSN of a record, in file B and whose LAST.NAME is the same as the, LAST.NAME of the record in file B, then the duplicate, rating of the record in file A is 20 (10 for SSN plus, 10 for LAST.NAME).  Since 20 is greater than 15, the, record in file A is considered a duplicate of the, record in file B., , When a record containing a duplicate is found,, the category is set to D for duplicate to show that, the rating identified it as a duplicate.  This, category is in the ....DUPL file, where ... is an, intermediate database file name.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: DUPL.FIELD.RATINGS
PURPOSE: The name of a user subroutine to be invoked for each, entry in the association.  The input to this routine, would be the associated field, weight and penalty; the, output would be a rating., , This subroutine could be used in instances where there, is a user algorithm for determining duplications other, than by getting an exact match.  The Colleague routines, always check for a value being equal to another; if, there is a way of specifying "close" (like, this address, is "close" to another because a ZIP code has changed),, this routine could be used to check for that., , Arguments:, A.SOURCE.VALUE (Input) - The value of the field on the,   intermediate file that is being compared, A.TARGET.VALUE (Input) - The value of the field on the,   Colleague file that is being compared, A.TARGET.ID (Input) - This is the ID of the target record,   in the Colleague database that we are comparing, A.WEIGHT (Input) - The weight rating for this source,   and target combination from the ELF.DUPL.CRITERIA record, A.PENALTY (Input) - The penalty for this source and target,   combination from the ELF.DUPL.CRITERIA record, A.ELF.DUPL.CRITERIA (Input) - The ID of ELF.DUPL.CRITERIA,   record being used to evaluate the duplicate checking, A.SOURCE.RECORD (Input) - The entire record from the,   intermediate file, A.IMPORT.RECORD (Input) - The entire import record.  This,   is the record that the import routine has built that,   will be written to the Colleague file, A.TARGET.RECORD (Input) - The Colleague record being evaluated.,   This is the entire record that for which we are currently,   calculating a duplicate rating, A.RATING (Output) - The rating for this particular field.,   The overall rating for the Colleague record will be,   incremented by this rating.  A positive rating increases,   the likelihood that the record will be considered a,   duplicate, and a negative rating decreases that likelihood, ABORT.MSG (Input/Output) - This is a field-delimited list,    of error messages, and may already contain message on,    input.  Messages describing any errors encountered,    should be added to this list

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: DUPL.FIELD.RATINGS
PURPOSE: These is the name of the intermediate file field that, will be used in deciding whether or not one record, is a duplicate of another., , If this field is multi-valued, the entire set of the, intermediate record is compared to the entire set of, the existing record.  There will be no attempt made, to compare all the possible permutations to find, a match.
The Colleague file to which the duplicate criteria, applies.  Used in the ELF process to resolve duplicates.
This is the name of the intermediate file to which, this duplicate criteria record applies.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: DUPL.SELECTS
PURPOSE: This field is a performance enhancer.  It tells the, duplicate checking routine which subsets of records to, select., , For example, suppose the limit field were INT.LAST.NAME in, an intermediate file.  This field could then be LAST.NAME, in PERSON.  This says to limit the records to check for, duplicates to the set of records in PERSON where the, intermediate file last name matches the LAST.NAME field, in PERSON.  Then the duplicate algorithms just deal, with the subset of the PERSON file that have the same, last name as the intermediate file.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: DUPL.SELECTS
PURPOSE: This field is a performance enhancer.  It tells the, duplicate checking routine which subsets of records to, select., , For example, suppose this field were INT.LAST.NAME in, an intermediate file.  The limiting comparison field, could be LAST.NAME in PERSON.  This says to limit, the records to check for duplicates to the set of, records in person where the intermediate file last, name matches the LAST.NAME field in PERSON.  Then, the duplicate algorithms just deal with the subset, of the PERSON file that have the same last name, as the intermediate file., , Without this type of field, each record in the, intermediate file would have to be compared to, each record in the PERSON file every time, leading, to a huge performance hit.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: DUPL.SELECTS
PURPOSE: The name of a user subroutine to be invoked for each, entry in the association.  The input to this routine, would be the associated fields; the output would be a, list of Colleague record IDs that would be the subset, of records to check for duplicates., , This subroutine could be used in instances where there, is a user algorithm to figure out which records could, be possible duplicates., , Arguments:, A.SOURCE.VALUE (Input) - The value of the field on the,   intermediate file that is being used to limit the view, A.ELF.DUPL.CRITERIA (Input) - The ID of ELF.DUPL.CRITERIA,   record being used to evaluate the duplicate checking, A.SOURCE.RECORD (Input) - The entire record from the,   intermediate file, A.IMPORT.RECORD (Input) - The entire import record.  This,   is the record that the import routine has built that,   will be written to the target file, AL.TARGET.IDS (Output) - A list of IDs that were,   determined to be potential duplicates.  Each ID passed,   back in this list will be read and a duplicate rating,   will be calculated, ABORT.MSG (Input/Output) - This is a field-delimited list,   of error messages, and may already contain message on,   input.  Messages describing any errors encountered,   should be added to this list

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: DUPL.FIELD.RATINGS
PURPOSE: This is an integer signifying a penalty if data is, different between two records., , When a record is evaluated to see if it is a duplicate,, these penalties are added together when the values in the, associated fields are different between two records., The sum of the weights, minus these penalties, is then, compared to the duplicate rating number.  If the sum, is greater than or equal to the duplicate rating,, the record is considered a duplicate of an existing, record; if the sum is less than the duplicate rating, but greater than or equal to the possible duplicate, rating, the record is considered to be a possible, duplicate of an existing record., , For example, suppose that the duplicate rating is 15,, that a field called SSN has a weight of 10, that, a field called LAST.NAME has a weight of 10, and, that a field called FIRST.NAME has a penalty of 8., If file A is being compared to file B, and file A, has a record whose SSN matches the SSN of a record, in file B, and whose LAST.NAME is the same as the, LAST.NAME of the record in file B, but whose FIRST.NAME, is not the same as the FIRST.NAME of the record in file, B, then the duplicate rating of the record in file A is, 12 (10 for SSN plus 10 for LAST.NAME, minus 8 for the, FIRST.NAME discrepancy).  Since 12 is less than 15, the, record in file A is NOT considered a duplicate of the, record in file B.

An integer specifying if two records are possibly, duplicates of each other., , When a record is evaluated to see if it is a duplicate,, the weights are added together when the values in the, associated fields are the same between two records., The penalties are subtracted when the values in the, associated fields are different between the two records., The sum of the weights, minus the penalties, is then, compared to the duplicate rating number.  If the sum, is greater than or equal to the duplicate rating,, the record is considered a duplicate of an existing, record; if the sum is less than the duplicate rating, but greater than or equal to this possible duplicate, rating, the record is considered to be a possible, duplicate of an existing record., , For example, suppose that the duplicate rating is 15,, that the possible duplicate rating is 10, that a, field called SSN has a weight of 10, and that a field, called LAST.NAME has a weight of 10.  If file A is, being compared to file B, and file A has a record, whose SSN matches the SSN of a record in file B and, whose LAST.NAME is the same as the LAST.NAME of the, record in file B, then the duplicate rating of the, record in file A is 20 (10 for SSN plus 10 for, LAST.NAME).  Since 20 is greater than 15, the, record in file A is considered a duplicate of the, record in file B.  However, if the LAST.NAMEs, were not the same, the rating would be 10; since, 10 is less than 15, but greater than or equal to, the possible duplicate rating of 10, the record, in file A is considered a possible duplicate of, the record in file B., , When a record containing a possible duplicate is found,, the category is set to P for Possibly duplicate to show, that the rating identified it as a possible duplicate., This category is in the ....DUPL file, where ... is an, intermediate database file name.

The name of a user-defined subroutine used to do, duplicate checking.  If this subroutine exists, all, other fields on the duplicate criteria record are, ignored; however, they can be entered for use by this, subroutine., , Arguments:, A.TARGET.ID (Input) - The ID of the Colleague record, for which a rating is being calculated, , A.ELF.DUPL.CRITERIA (Input) - The ID of ELF.DUPL.CRITERIA, record being used to evaluate the duplicate checking, , A.SOURCE.RECORD (Input) - The entire record from the, intermediate file, , A.IMPORT.RECORD (Input) - The entire import record.  This, is the record that the import routine has built that, will be written to the target file, , A.TARGET.RECORD (Input) - The target record being evaluated., This is the entire record that for which we are currently, calculating a duplicate rating, , A.RATING (Output) - The duplicate rating for this Colleague, record., , ABORT.MSG (Input/Output) - This is a field-delimited list, of error messages, and may already contain message on, input.  Messages describing any errors encountered, should be added to this list

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: DUPL.FIELD.RATINGS
PURPOSE: This is an integer signifying the relative importance, of the associated field., , When a record is evaluated to see if it is a duplicate,, these weights are added together when the values in the, associated fields are the same between two records., The sum of the weights, minus the penalties, is then, compared to the duplicate rating number.  If the sum, is greater than or equal to the duplicate rating,, the record is considered a duplicate of an existing, record; if the sum is less than the duplicate rating, but greater than or equal to the possible duplicate, rating, the record is considered to be a possible, duplicate of an existing record., , For example, suppose that the duplicate rating is 15,, that a field called SSN has a weight of 10, and, that a field called LAST.NAME has a weight of 10., If file A is being compared to file B, and file A, has a record whose SSN matches the SSN of a record, in file B and whose LAST.NAME is the same as the, LAST.NAME of the record in file B, then the duplicate, rating of the record in file A is 20 (10 for SSN plus, 10 for LAST.NAME).  Since 20 is greater than 15, the, record in file A is considered a duplicate of the, record in file B.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: ELFINTER.DEPS
PURPOSE: The name of the fields on the intermediate file, that will be related to other fields in other, intermediate files for the purposes of importing to the, Colleague/Benefactor database.  This must be the name, of a field in the intermediate file., , The information here is used to determine what other, intermediate file records are needed to complete a, transaction set.  For example, the intermediate file, called INTER.TEST.SCORE may be all fields from, STUDENT.NON.COURSES.  This would mean that some, person information would be required for a new, STUDENT.NON.COURSES record to be created.  So, INTER.TEST.SCORE would have an entry in this field, for ITSTSC.PERSON.ID, which would then be related, to IBIO.PERSON.ID in INTER.BIODEMO to show that, the two fields need the same value.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: ELFINTER.DEPS

This would mean that some, person information would be required for a new, STUDENT.NON.COURSES record to be created.  So, INTER.TEST.SCORE would have an entry in the , ELFINTER.FIELDS field for ITSTSC.PERSON.ID.  This, ELFINTER.RELATED.FIELDS would then have an entry, for IBIO.PERSON.ID in INTER.BIODEMO to show that, the two fields need the same value.

This is the prefix to be used whenever this target, field is referenced in relation to the associated, source field.  It is primarily used to group a set of, target fields to allow mapping one source record to, multiple instances of the same target file., , For example, say fields 5, 6 and 7 of a source file, mapped to fields A, B and C of file X.  That would, create one record in file X.  If fields 8, 9 and, 10 also mapped to fields A, B and C of file X, but, were to create a new record, then in the mapping, of fields 8 to A, fields 9 to B and fields 10 to C,, the same logical prefix would be given to those, 3 mappings.  This would tell the generator that, the fields 5/6/7 mapping creates one record and, the 8/9/10 mapping creates another.  This is, common on tapes that have test scores.  One set, of tests needs to create one record in, STUDENT.NON.COURSES and another set needs to, create another record in STUDENT.NON.COURSES,, both for the same person., , Note that when a logical prefix is specified for, target fields, the required fields of the target, file all need the logical prefix as well.  The, generator will not get any fields from the previous, instance of the target file.  In other words, if, the following mapping exists:, , Source    Target   Logical Pfx, , Test Name      A.TEST.NAME, Test Score 1   A.TEST.SCORE, Test Score 1 Date   A.TEST.SCORE.DATE, Test Score 2   A.TEST.SCORE  SCORE2, Test Score 2 Date   A.TEST.SCORE.DATE  SCORE2, , If the record for Score 2 also needed the test name,, an additional mapping needs to be specified:, , Source    Target   Logical Pfx, , Test Name A.TEST.NAME   SCORE2, , Since a source field can be mapped to multiple, targets, this is an acceptable mapping., , So it is not assumed that just because test name, went on the first record, it will be put on the, second as well.  This needs to be explicitly mapped., , Any non-generated code (hook code, etc.) needs to, reference the prefix to keep the record instances, straight.  So to deal with the first record, the, field names are A.TEST.NAME, etc.  To deal with, the second record, the field names are, SCORE2.A.TEST.SCORE, etc.
The action to take in case of translate failure.  See, the valcode ELF.TRANSLATE.ACTIONS for more information.
This is the name of a translate table to be used in, this mapping.  If a table is specified here, it, overrides the table (if any) specified for the source, field.
This tells what is to be done when a target value is, in error (when it fails the validations).  , See the ELF.VALUE.ERROR.ACTIONS validation, code table for more information.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: MERGE.ASSOCIATIONS
PURPOSE: This is the merge action to use for the associated, association. See the ELF.MERGE.ACTIONS validation code, table for more information on the effect of the, action codes when merging data.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: MERGE.ASSOCIATIONS
PURPOSE: The name of a user subroutine to be invoked for the, associated association.  The input to this routine, would be the association field values; the output, would be the new association field values., , This subroutine could be used in instances where there, is a user algorithm for determining how an association, is to be merged with the source data that goes beyond, what the specification handles.  For example, Colleague, cannot delete just one entry from an association; if, that is needed, and an algorithm is known to do that,, this routine could specify that algorithm., , Arguments:, , AL.FIELD.NAMES (Input) - A field-delimited list of field, names.  This is used to determine what data corresponds to, each field in the association, , AL.IMPORT.VALUES (Input) - This is a field-delimited list,, associated to AL.FIELD.NAMES.  It contains the values from, the record that the import routine built for each field in, the association., , AL.TARGET.VALUES (Input) - This is a field-delimited list,, associated to AL.FIELD.NAMES.  It contains the values from, the existing Colleague record being updated for each field in, the association., , A.ELF.MERGE.CRITERIA (Input) - The ID of ELF.MERGE.CRITERIA, record being used to merge the data, , A.IMPORT.RECORD (Input) - The entire import record.  This, is the record that the import routine has built that, will be written to the Colleague file, , A.TARGET.RECORD (Input) - The entire Colleague record being updated, , AL.NEW.VALUES (Output) - This is a field-delimited list,, associated to AL.FIELD.NAMES.  It contains the new values, for each field in the association, to be stored on the, merged record., , ABORT.MSG (Input/Output) - This is a field-delimited list, of error messages, and may already contain message on, input.  Messages describing any errors encountered, should be added to this list

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: MERGE.ASSOCIATIONS
PURPOSE: These are associations on ELFMERG.FILE that need to be, handled differently from ELFMERG.DEFAULT.ACTION when, merged.
Free-form text about this merge criteria.

This is the field that will be used to determine if, the data being imported should affect the Colleague, data.  The value of the field specified here will be, checked for each record against the date entered on, the front end screen of an intermediate to Colleague, import., , For example, if a tape of addresses is being loaded,, the most current address is what is desired.  If this, field has ADDRESS.CHANGE.DATE2, then the value of, ADDRESS.CHANGE.DATE2 of a record on the ADDRESS file, that is to have data merged into it will be compared, to a date entered on the import front end screen., Only if the value on the front end screen is greater, than the value in ADDRESS.CHANGE.DATE2 will the, data be updated in Colleague.  So if ADDRESS.CHANGE.DATE2, has 8/8/97 and the front end screen has 7/7/97, the, existing ADDRESS record will not be modified.

The default action to use when merging data.  If no, specific action is specified for a field, this, default action will control how the data on the, import record is merged with the data on the Colleague, record.  See the ELF.MERGE.ACTIONS validation code, table for more information on the effect of the, action codes when merging data.
A description of the merge criteria.  Displayed on, resolution screens.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: MERGE.FIELDS
PURPOSE: This is the merge action to use for the associated, field. See the ELF.MERGE.ACTIONS validation code, table for more information on the effect of the, action codes when merging data.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: MERGE.FIELDS
PURPOSE: The name of a user subroutine to be invoked for the, associated field.  The input to this routine, would be the field values; the output, would be the new field values., , This subroutine could be used in instances where there, is a user algorithm for determining how a field is to, be merged with the source data that goes beyond what, the specification handles.  For example, Colleague, cannot delete just one entry from a list; if that is, needed, and an algorithm is known to do that, this, routine could specify that algorithm., , Arguments:, , AL.SOURCE.VALUES (Input) - The value of the field on the, intermediate file; multi-valued to allow for lists, , AL.TARGET.VALUES (Input) - The value of the field on the, Colleague file; multi-valued to allow for lists, , A.ELF.MERGE.CRITERIA (Input) - The ID of ELF.MERGE.CRITERIA, record being used to merge the data, , A.IMPORT.RECORD (Input) - The entire import record.  This, is the record that the import routine has built that, will be written to the Colleague file, , A.TARGET.RECORD (Input) - The entire original Colleague, record being updated, , AL.NEW.VALUES (Output) - The new field value that will be, written to the Colleague file, , ABORT.MSG (Input/Output) - This is a field-delimited list, of error messages, and may already contain message on, input.  Messages describing any errors encountered, should be added to this list

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: MERGE.FIELDS
PURPOSE: These are fields on ELFMERG.FILE that need to be, handled differently from ELFMERG.DEFAULT.ACTION when, merged.  These are only stand-alone fields.  Fields, which belong to an association must be specified, through ELFMERG.ASSOCIATIONS.
This is the Colleague file to which the merge criteria, applies.

The name of a user-defined subroutine used to merge, data with an existing record.  If this subroutine, exists, all other fields on the merge criteria record, are ignored; however, they can be entered for use by, this subroutine., , Arguments:, , A.TARGET.ID (Input) - The ID of the Colleague record, in which data will be merged, , A.ELF.MERGE.CRITERIA (Input) - The ID of ELF.MERGE.CRITERIA, record being used to merge data, , A.IMPORT.RECORD (Input) - The entire import record.  This, is the record that the import routine has built that, will be written to the target file, , A.TARGET.RECORD (Input) - The entire original Colleague record, being updated, , A.NEW.RECORD (Output) - The entire replacement Colleague record, , ABORT.MSG (Input/Output) - This is a field-delimited list, of error messages, and may already contain message on, input.  Messages describing any errors encountered, should be added to this list

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: ELF.PURGE
PURPOSE: Stores the ELF map name when a source file should be , purged at the same time as the batch.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: ELF.PURGE
PURPOSE: Contains the name of the file storing the source , records for the ELF batch to be deleted.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: ELF.PURGE
PURPOSE: The ELF batch purge program is assuming that the source, file is keyed the same as the batch. If the source file, has an additional suffix, such as .csv, that is entered, here.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: EFSPT.ORA.COMMENTS
PURPOSE: Free-form text about this ELF specification target, file.  Displayed but not otherwise used by the system.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: ELFSPCTGT.NEWRECS
PURPOSE: This field "controls" how many records will be created for, this target file.  This must be a field from the source, file.  If this field is multivalued, one record will be , created/updated in the target file for each value found, in this field, including null values.  If this field is , left blank, or is null or single-valued, then a single , target record will be created. , , This field is not used during the specification of an ITC, (intermediate-to-Colleague) specification since an ITC, process only allows for a single record per target file.

Yes/no flag saying whether or not the target record, is always to be written.  The default is Yes; Yes, means that the target record will be built and, potentially written based on defaults and whatever, exists in the source file., , No means that the source fields that map to this, target file are checked; if all those source fields, are null, the target record is not built and not, written.  This flag would only be set to No in, specialized cases where one source maps to multiple, targets, and only a portion of a source record might, exist in some records and only one of the multiple, targets is to be created for those records.
The ID of a duplicate criterion record.  This is used, to get the specifications of what constitutes a, duplicate record in this target file.
The name of the target file.  Used to, restrict the fields that can be used in the, associated ELF specification mapping, as well, as to include the proper file equates in the, generated code.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: EFSPT.ORA.KEY
PURPOSE: This is hook code that can be used to override the, normal key creation of a target file.  It is often, used on conversions, when the key may be system-, generated but the existing value needs to be kept., , There is only one key hook per target file, even if, the target file has a multi-part key.  If this, hook exists, it overrides automatic generation of, a new key.  If it does not exist, the system will, automatically generate a sequential key by calling, S.NEXT.KEY., , Active Variables:,  KEY.<filename> - This should be set to the full key,     of the target record on output,  ERROR.OCCURRED,  WARNING.OCCURRED,  MSG,  MSG.ARGUMENTS
The default merge criteria record to use when, merging data from an import record with an existing, record in Colleague.  This may be overridden at, run-time by the end user.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: EFSPT.ORA.WRITE
PURPOSE: This code is executed after all the target fields for a, target record have been processed, but before the target, record is actually rebuilt.  This is a place where each, target record can be manipulated with the V. and VL., variables available.  These are the active variables., , This hook is NOT to be used to do file validation that, applies to the file in every circumstance.  It is ONLY, to be used to do special things that apply to the file, in the scope of a particular ELF specification., , Extreme care must be taken to not put file integrity, rules into this hook.  Any validation that is for the, target record as a whole and only relies on the target, record field values to do its work should be put in, the pre-create hook (RT.FILES.PRE.CREATE.HOOK) or the, pre-update hook (RT.FILES.PRE.UPDT.HOOK) of the target, file.  This pre-write hook should only be used to set, values.  Be aware that the pre-create hook and pre-update, hook are run after this hook., , This should not be used for doing standard defaulting., Standard defaulting should be done either in the field, default hook (RTFLDS.DEFAULT.HOOK on EFS003 (RDEP)), in, the default value (RTFLDS.DEFAULT.VALUE on EFS003 (RDEP)),, or in the map itself (ELFMAP.POST.EDIT.HOOK or ELFMAP.LIST., EXIT.HOOK on EFS015 (ELMD)).  If the default depends on, other fields of the file, then the code should go in the, pre-create hook (RT.FILES.PRE.CREATE.HOOK on EFS001 (RFSP)).

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: ELFSPCTGT.NEWRECS
PURPOSE: This field serves to identify multiple mapping schemes, to the same target file.   , , If, as in most cases, there is only one mapping , scheme for a target file, then a prefix is not , needed., , For example, suppose a , source file contains PERSON data that we wish to map to, two different records of the INT.PERSON file.  The , incoming source record is layed out such that , , Field 10, MOTHER.LAST.NAME, provides the first person's last name and, Field 11 provides the first person's first name, , Field 25, FATHER.LAST.NAME provides the second person's last name., Field 26 provides the second person's first name, , In this case, create the target file as:, , File name      = INT.PERSON, Control fields = MOTHER.LAST.NAME}FATHER.LAST.NAME, Prefixes  = X}Y, , In the field mappings, the prefix is referenced to, differentiate the target records.  This particular, example would contain the following 4 field maps:, , Source field 10 ----> Field LAST.NAME of ,   target file INT.PERSON,   ELFMAP.TGT.LOGICAL.PREFIX = X, Source field 11 ----> Field FIRST.NAME of ,   target file INT.PERSON,   ELFMAP.TGT.LOGICAL.PREFIX = X, , Source field 25 ----> Field LAST.NAME of ,   target file INT.PERSON,   ELFMAP.TGT.LOGICAL.PREFIX = Y, Source field 26 ----> Field FIRST.NAME of ,   target file INT.PERSON,   ELFMAP.TGT.LOGICAL.PREFIX = Y
The ELF specification record for which this is a , target file.  This is an ID of an ELF.SPECS record.
The application in which this ELF transfer will run., This is used to control which files can be used in, the transfer, etc.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: EFSP.ORA.COMMENTS
PURPOSE: Any free-form text about this ELectronic File, specification.  Displayed but not otherwise used by, the system.
Brief description of the specification.  Displays on, resolution screens.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: EFSP.ORA.INT.ROUTINE
PURPOSE: These are internal routines that can be called by, other hook code in the generated code.  These routines, must follow normal conventions of internal routines, that can be invoked via GOSUBs.  The internal routine, name must also be provided as part of the code.
A list of keys to the ELF.MAPS file.  The ELF.MAPS, file has the detail of field to field mapping.  It is, used to get to the details of the field mapping.
Contains named common label as determined by the, generator.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: EFSP.ORA.PRCS.ENTRY
PURPOSE: This is code that gets executed during initialization, and set up.  The code or module is executed once --, just before the program enters the main processing loop., Because the code is executed before the user has any, opportunity to interact with the process, the code is, always executed. It is executed prior to any file reads, and should only contain initialization-type code.  The, most common use of this field is to initialize custom, variables used elsewhere in a process to avoid "Variable, Unassigned" error messages., , Active Variables,  ABORT.MSG - field-delimited list of error messages.,    If set, the process will abort without processing,    any records.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: EFSP.ORA.PRCS.EXIT
PURPOSE: This code will execute at the end of the generated, ELectronic File transfer program.  This code is, executed before the standard wrap up code inserted, by the generator.   This is a rarely-used hook;, it is primarily used when a group of records on, one or more of the target files needs to be, manipulated to create something on yet another, target file(s)., , Active Variables: None.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: EFSP.ORA.PRE.COMMIT
PURPOSE: This code is executed after the target records have been, built and written out using MIO, but before they have, been physically written to disk.  This is a place where, the entire transaction set can be manipulated., (Individual record hooks are in RT.FILES, in the, create/read/update/delete hook fields.), , Active Variables,  R.<target files> - available only through MIO reads and,     writes,  ERROR.OCCURRED,  WARNING.OCCURRED,  MSG,  MSG.ARGUMENTS
This is the primary input file for the file transfer, spec.  The main loop in the generated program will, read and process each record in this primary file, from the active SAVEDLIST.

This is the list of files that will be used as input, for use in creating or updating fields in other files, in this ELF spec.  The files referred to in this list, are used to restrict the fields that can be entered, in the mapping source fields; only fields from one of, the files entered here or in the primary source, file can be referenced., , Code will be generated to read each of these, source files for each record in the primary, input file., , 10 Apr 1996  08:38pm  Sylvia Gelabert, Note:  this is not used at this time.  Only single, file input will be supported initially.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: EFSP.ORA.SRC.PRE.ED
PURPOSE: This code will execute after a record has been read,, and before any field edits are performed.  This, would be used to do things like read other source, file records to pre-assign fields in the primary, file, etc., , Active Variables:,  R.<source file>,  ERROR.OCCURRED,  WARNING.OCCURRED,  MSG,  MSG.ARGUMENTS

This is a list of IDs to the ELF.SPEC.TGTS, file, which has the list of files containing, the target data which will be updated as a, result of the electronic transfer.  The files, referred to by the IDs in this list are, used to restrict the fields that can be, entered in the mapping target fields; only, fields from one of the files referenced here, can be used as targets., , Code will be generated to read and/or, write each of these target files for each, record in the primary input file based, on information in the ELF.SPEC.TGTS record, for this ELF spec for this file.

PURPOSE: Contains special processing data

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: ELFTBL
PURPOSE: Contains second special processing data

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: ELFTBL
PURPOSE: Contains data for special processing

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: ELFTBL

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: ELFT.ORA.COMMENTS
PURPOSE: Free-form text about the translate table.  Displayed, but not otherwise used by the system.
Description of the translations.  Displayed but not, otherwise used except on resolution screens.

This is the name of the field against which values in, the new code field should be validated.  Whatever, the validation table/file specified for the field named, here will be used to validate the new codes., , For example, if external course levels are to be, translated to internal values, then the name CRS.LEVEL, would be entered here.  Then any values specified in, the new code would be validated however CRS.LEVEL, values are validated., , If this field is left blank, any value can be, entered in the new codes column and no validation, will be done.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: ELFTBL
PURPOSE: Contains the value which the target field will have., This can be null in case an incoming value is not, to have any value in the target file.

This is the name of the field against which values in, the original code field should be validated.  Whatever, the validation table/file specified for the field named, here will be used to validate the original codes., , For example, if internal course levels are to be, translated to external values, then the name CRS.LEVEL, would be entered here.  Then any values specified in, the original code would be validated however CRS.LEVEL, values are validated., , If this field is left blank, any value can be, entered in the original code column and no validation, will be performed.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: ELFTBL
PURPOSE: Contains list of original codes associated to new codes.

The batch name of the intermediate file record.  This, is the batch with which this record is associated.  , Maintained but not otherwise used by the system., , This field is system-maintained and not meant to be, modified by users.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: DUPLS
PURPOSE: This is the category assigned to the associated, ID by the duplicate checking routine.  The category, depends on which threshold the rating exceeded.  The, higher the record's rating, the higher its category., , This field is system-maintained and not meant to be, modified by users.

This is the ID of the ELF.DUPL.CRITERIA record that, was used in duplicate checking.  It is kept for, historical purposes and not otherwise used by the, system.  It is system-maintained and not meant to be, modified by users.  Changing this will NOT change the, duplicate criteria used for the purposes of determining, a duplicate record.

The date the duplicate match process was last run., If any duplicates were detected, this is also the , date data in the duplicate association was created., , Used to give a comparison date between the date the, data is loaded to the target file and the date the, duplicate checking was done since a period of time, may have elapsed between one and the other.  If, time has passed, the old duplicate checking results, may no longer be trustworthy., , This field is system-maintained and not meant to be, modified by users.

The ID of the one record which the duplicate checking , routine has determined is a duplicate of the data, being imported., , This data is maintained only by the duplicate checking, routine.  It is entered only when that routine is able, to find a match, and only if there is absolutely no, ambiguity which requires manual resolution.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: DUPLS
PURPOSE: The duplicate probability rating of the associated ID., , This is the numerical rating of probability of being a, duplicate, which the duplicate checking routine came, up with for this record., , This field is system-maintained and not meant to be, modified by users.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: DUPLS
PURPOSE: The duplicate IDs that were found on the target files., Here are listed all the IDs whose duplicate probability, rating met or exceeded a minimum threshold during the , duplicate checking process., , This field is system-maintained and not meant to be, modified by users.

The name of the intermediate file from which these, results were obtained.  This is used primarily as a, visual cue to what originated the results record; the, system normally accesses the target results file from, the intermediate file, not vice versa.  However, to, get to the intermediate file from this target results, file, this field would tell which file to read., , This field is system-maintained and not meant to be, modified by users.

These are the names of the fields on the intermediate, file that make up the key of the target file.  If the, target ID is a multi-part key, this will be the, individual fields that make up the ID.  They will be, in the order of the target ID.  For example, if the, target file is INSTITUTIONS.ATTEND, whose key is, person ID*institution ID, then this list would have, IIA.PERSON.ID and IIA.INST.ID, which are the fields, from the INTER.INST.ATTEND file., , The information to fill in these fields comes from, the mappings.  The mapping specifications say which, fields on the intermediate files go to which target, file fields, and the CDD specifications say which are, the key fields of the target file.  This information, then gives the fields of the intermediate file that, were used as keys of the target file., , This field is system-maintained and not to be modified, by users.

This is the key of the intermediate file record to, which these results are related.  This, along with the, intermediate file name, tells from where this results, record came., , This field is system-maintained and not meant to be, modified by users.

This is the ID of the ELF.MERGE.CRITERIA record that, was used to update an existing record.  It is kept for, historical purposes and not otherwise used by the, system.  It is system-maintained and not meant to be, modified by users.  Changing this will NOT change the, merge criteria used for the purposes of updating an, existing record.

This stores all the IDs which the user has manually, identified as "definitely not a duplicate".  This review, process will usually be done after the user gets a , duplicates report indicating that one or more records, have ambiguities that require manual resolution., If the user determines that NONE of the IDs , suggested as possible dups by the duplicate , checking routine are duplicates of the data being, imported, then the user should enter those IDs, into ELFTGT.NON.DUPL.IDS.  This flags those, IDs as non-duplicates, and will prevent them from again, being flagged as possible duplicates the next time, duplicate checking is rerun.   Note, if, ELFTGT.OVERRIDE.ID is filled in,  that is, if the , user has manually specified which ID is the , true duplicate, then there is no need to , enter anything into ELFTGT.NON.DUPL.IDS,, since duplicate checking will not be run again.

This stores the ID which the user has manually, determined is a duplicate of the data being, imported.  This field can be used to override, ELFTGT.DUPL.ID (the ID suggested by the duplicate, checking routine).
The status of the target record.  See ELF.TGT.STATUSES, validation code table for more information., , This field is system-maintained and not meant to be, modified by users.

Yes/no flag saying whether or not to reject all the, duplicates identified in the Dupl Target ID group, of TGTR (EFS025).  If yes, it means none of the, duplicates identified in the Dupl Target ID list, are really duplicates.  If no, it means there is, still a possibility of one of the list being a, duplicate ID., , This is a shorthand way of saying none of the duplicate, IDs really are duplicates.  The alternative way would, have been to replicate the Dupl Target ID list in the, Non-Dupl IDs list.  This would get cumbersome if a, lot of IDs had been noted as possible duplicates.

COMPUTED.COLUMN.CODE: string xResult1; , xResult1 = SValcodeDesc("CORE", vElftgtRecordStatus, "ELF.TGT.STATUSES");, return xResult1;

PURPOSE: The target file for which these are the results., This is a Colleague file name, not an inter-, mediate file.  This would be a target file of the, intermediate file mapping., , This field is system-maintained and not meant to be, modified by users.

This is the actual ID which ended up being, updated or created in the target Colleague, file.   This field is not filled in until, the intermediate to Colleague procedure, successfully processes this record while, running in update mode.

This is the transaction which created this target, result record.  This, with the batch in ELFTGT.BATCH,, relates this target result with the transaction record, in ELF.TRANSACTIONS that created it.  Kept but not, otherwise used by the system., , This field is system-maintained and not meant to be, modified by users.

This field provides a mechanism to create an ELF , transaction which should not be processed (imported, into Colleague) until on or after a certain date., If a transaction is created with an ACTION.DATE, , then the ITC (intermediate-to-Colleague) phase of, the import will skip the transaction until on, or after that date.
First part of key to ELF.TRANSACTIONS., The ELF.TRANSACTIONS file is keyed by ,    batch.id * transaction.cntr.  , The batch ID is the user-selected name of the batch.

PURPOSE: Contains the index values for selection in ITCI.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: ELFCONTROL.FILES
PURPOSE: The ID of the record in the associated intermediate, database file which was created during the first phase, (the STI, or source-to-intermediate phase) of an , import process., , The ELFTRANS.INTER.FILE and ELFTRANS.RECORD.IDS fields, form an association which lists all the intermediate , database records created for this transaction., , This field is system-maintained and not meant to be, modified by users.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: ELFCONTROL.FILES
PURPOSE: The status of each associated intermediate file.  This, is provided for performance reasons and ease of, programming.  Without it, in order to determine if, an intermediate file has been succesfully imported,, we would need to read that intermediate file and, then read its ELF.TGT.RESULTS records and get their, statuses.  This is difficult in the ITC batch,, which would have to open each intermediate file, on-the-fly in order to read it and get the keys, to the ELF.TGT.RESULTS records.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: ELFCONTROL.FILES
PURPOSE: The name of the intermediate file that was written to, for the batch and transaction in the key.  Used to know, what intermediate file to access., , The fields ELFTRANS.INTER.FILES and ELFTRANS.RECORD.IDS, form an association which lists all the intermediate file, records which were created for this transaction by the , Source-to-intermediate (STI) process., , This field is system-maintained and not meant to be, modified by users.

This is an error message for the STI phase of an import process., If present, it indicates that an error occurred which prevented, the transaction from being processed properly.   A multi-line , error can be logged by using @VM to delimit the lines.
This is a list of Warning messages that were generated, for this transaction.  Warnings are delimited by @VMs, and, lines within a warning are delimited by @SM.

DEFAULT.SAMPLE.DATA: Manual resolution of duplicate records required.

The US Immigration and Naturalization Service Student and Exchange, Visitor Information System (SEVIS) requires requires a program, sponsor code to be reported on the header for exchange visitors., This code was assigned by the Immigration and Naturalization, Service (INS).  That code should be assigned to the sponsor, entered here in the Alternate IDs field on AORG, Additional, Organization Information, if the sponsor is an organization, or, on DADD, Additional Demographics, if the sponsor is a person,, with an associated alternate ID Types that matches the, Sponsor Alt ID Type on SEVP, SEVIS Parameters.  When formatting the, header for SEVIS exchange visitor reporting, the CORP or PERSON, record of the Colleague ID entered here is used to determine, which program sponsor code to report based on what was entered, on SEVP and AORG or DADD., , The sponsor entered here must have an entry in alternate ID Types, on AORG or DADD that matches the Sponsor Alt ID Type on SEVP., , This defaults from the sponsor entered on SEVP and can be changed, as needed.

These are US government agencies that provided funding, to the sponsor to support the exchange visitor.  Defaults, from SEVP.SPONSOR.GOVT.AGENCIES but can be changed as, needed.  Not used by the system, but can be used for, manually producing the IAP-66/DS-2019.

The I-94 Form is the entry document a non-citizen completes, when arriving in the US. A foreign visitor with re-entry, privileges such as a student is to keep the same I-94 number,, actually called the Admission Number, for the entire authorized, period of study.  The number would be copied onto the student's, I-20 form. When the student goes home for the summer, he/she, surrenders the I-94 card (in theory at least). When he/she, returns to the US, the number on the new I-94 would be marked, out and the original Admission Number would be written in by the, Immigration and Naturalization Service (INS) Officer (the form, was designed for that purpose).  The original I-94 Number (the, Admission Number) would be the foreign student's number for the, entire period of study., , The simple explanation is that the I-94 number is the number INS, uses to track the student.  (Richard Elliott's explanation)

This allows setting up a generic "other" value in the, valcode and then putting the correct description here.  It is, also useful for student school funds descriptions., , While this can be entered for any funding source, it is, only reported to SEVIS for people seeking to become students,, not for exchange visitors.

A source to intermediate import should *never* set this field., , This field is used internally by the ELF spec to implement the address, householding settings when finding ADDRESS duplicates. It is used, to pass information about the imported PERSON record to the ADDRESS, duplicate checking process. , , IBIO.ADDR.HOUSEHOLDING.INFO<1,1> contains the PERSON ID that has been, determined for the imported person, if one exists., , IBIO.ADDR.HOUSEHOLDING.INFO<1,2> is "N" to indicate the PERSON is not, a corp., , IBIO.ADDR.HOUSEHOLDING.INFO<1,3> contains the values in , IBIO.ADDRESS.TYPES, but delimited by @SM., , IBIO.ADDR.HOUSEHOLDING.INFO is set in the pre-write hook of the ADDRESS, target spec, and then passed to the limiting field subroutine, S.LIMIT.ADDRESS.DUPLICATES when it is specified as the limiting field., This method is necessary because this information about the PERSON, that is being imported is not available to the ADDRESS duplicate, checking otherwise. A source to intermediate import should *never* set this field., , This field is used internally by the ELF spec to implement the address, householding settings when finding ADDRESS duplicates. It is used, to pass information about the imported PERSON record to the ADDRESS, duplicate checking process. , , IEMP.ADDR.HOUSEHOLDING.INFO<1,1> contains the CORP ID that has been, determined for the imported CORP., , IEMP.ADDR.HOUSEHOLDING.INFO<1,2> is "N" to indicate the PERSON is not, a corp., , IEMP.ADDR.HOUSEHOLDING.INFO<1,3> contains an @SM delimited list of, source address types., , IEMP.ADDR.HOUSEHOLDING.INFO is set in the pre-write hook of the ADDRESS, target spec, and then passed to the limiting field subroutine, S.LIMIT.ADDRESS.DUPLICATES when it is specified as the limiting field., This information is essential to properly implement address householding., This is a standard field and method used in all the ELF specs that, import addresses.

This date as of which all of the academic credential, records for the person for the institution are to be, terminated.  It means that as of this date, regardless, of the end dates of the individual academic credential, records, the academic credentials are no longer valid., This could be the date an employee was terminated, or, some other date on which all certifications of all, academic credentials were revoked., , This is used in ST when determining if a person is qualified, to teach a course section.  When a faculty member is being, assigned to a course section, both qualifications and academic, credentials are checked to see if the faculty member should be, teaching the course section.  For the academic credential, the, end date normally determines if that credential can be applied, to the course section.  However, if the credential's, certification status has a value with a special processing, code of 1, this means the certification has been cancelled, or terminated, and the credential will not be seen as making, that faculty member eligible to teach the course section, regardless of the credential end date.  Also, if this, credential end date is filled in, it is the date that will, be used instead of the academic credential end date to, decide if the person is still eligible to be assigned, to a course section., , This credential end date takes precedence (that is, is used), over all certification statuses and all individual credential, end dates.  If entered on any home institution academic, credentials, it does not reverse any records created or marked, by the ST graduation process; these have to be manually deleted, on the HOME screen instead of using this credential end date.

A source to intermediate import should *never* set this field., , This field is used internally by the ELF spec to implement the address, householding settings when finding ADDRESS duplicates. It is used, to pass information about the imported PERSON record to the ADDRESS, duplicate checking process. , , IOA.ADDR.HOUSEHOLDING.INFO<1,1> contains the PERSON ID that has been, determined for the imported person, if one exists., , IOA.ADDR.HOUSEHOLDING.INFO<1,2> is "Y" if the PERSON is a CORP, "N", otherwise., , IOA.ADDR.HOUSEHOLDING.INFO<1,3> contains the values in , IOA.ADDRESS.TYPES, but delimited by @SM., , IOA.ADDR.HOUSEHOLDING.INFO is set in the pre-write hook of the ADDRESS, target spec, and then passed to the limiting field subroutine, S.LIMIT.ADDRESS.DUPLICATES when it is specified as the limiting field., This method is necessary because this information about the PERSON, that is being imported is not available to the ADDRESS duplicate, checking otherwise. This information is essential to properly , implement address householding.

A source to intermediate import should *never* set this field., , This field is used internally by the ELF spec to implement the address, householding settings when finding ADDRESS duplicates. It is used, to pass information about the imported PERSON record to the ADDRESS, duplicate checking process. , , IOCN.ADDR.HOUSEHOLDING.INFO<1,1> contains the PERSON ID that has been, determined for the imported person, if one exists., , IOCN.ADDR.HOUSEHOLDING.INFO<1,2> is "Y" if the PERSON is a CORP, "N", otherwise., , IOCN.ADDR.HOUSEHOLDING.INFO<1,3> contains the values in , IOA.ADDRESS.TYPES, but delimited by @SM., , IOCN.ADDR.HOUSEHOLDING.INFO is set in the pre-write hook of the ADDRESS, target spec, and then passed to the limiting field subroutine, S.LIMIT.ADDRESS.DUPLICATES when it is specified as the limiting field., This method is necessary because this information about the PERSON, that is being imported is not available to the ADDRESS duplicate, checking otherwise. This information is essential to properly , implement address householding.

A source to intermediate import should *never* set this field., , This field is used internally by the ELF spec to implement the address, householding settings when finding ADDRESS duplicates. It is used, to pass information about the imported PERSON record to the ADDRESS, duplicate checking process. , , IVEN.ADDR.HOUSEHOLDING.INFO<1,1> contains the PERSON ID that has been, determined for the imported person, if one exists., , IVEN.ADDR.HOUSEHOLDING.INFO<1,2> is "N" to indicate the PERSON is not, a corp., , IVEN.ADDR.HOUSEHOLDING.INFO<1,3> contains the values in , IVEN.ADDRESS.TYPES, but delimited by @SM., , IVEN.ADDR.HOUSEHOLDING.INFO is set in the pre-write hook of the ADDRESS, target spec, and then passed to the limiting field subroutine, S.LIMIT.ADDRESS.DUPLICATES when it is specified as the limiting field., This method is necessary because this information about the PERSON, that is being imported is not available to the ADDRESS duplicate, checking otherwise. This information is essential to properly , implement address householding.

This is the cutoff date for posting meal charges, immediately to AR., , If the meal post immediately flag is No, no meal, charges hit AR when the meal assignment is, created or a billing field on the meal assignment, is maintained.  A batch process to post the meal, assignments to AR will subsequently need to be run., , If the meal post immediately flag is set to Yes,, this cutoff date determines which meal assignments, immediately affect AR.  Any meal assignment whose, billing period start date is after this date will, not affect AR balances until a batch process is, run to post unposted meal assignments to AR.  Any, meal assignment whose billing period start date is, on or before this date will be posted to AR as soon, as the record is saved., , If this cutoff date is null and the meal post, immediately flag is set to Yes, then all meal, assignments will post to AR regardless of date, as soon as the meal assignment record is saved., , Defaults from AR.MEAL.POST.IMDTLY.DATE in, AR.DEFAULTS and can be changed.  If there is, no value for the location, the AR.DEFAULTS, date will be used.

Yes/no flag specifying whether or not room, charges and credits are to be posted to AR when they, are created.  No means that no room postings records, and no invoices will be created when the room, assignment is created or updated; so the AR account, will not reflect the room charges or credits until, a batch process runs to create the room postings and, invoices.  The batch process creating the invoice, then updates the AR account., , If Yes then room postings and invoice records may be, created immediately upon creating or updating a room, assignment record depending upon the values of the, billing period start date of the room assignment and, the billing cutoff date (see LOC.AR.ROOM.POST.IMDTLY.DATE)., , Defaults from AR.ROOM.POST.IMDTLY.FLAG in AR.DEFAULTS, and can be changed.  If there is no value for the, location, the AR.DEFAULTS value will be used.

This is the cutoff date for posting registration charges, immediately to AR., , If the registration post immediately flag is No, no, registration charges hit AR when the registration is, created or a billing field on the registration is, maintained.  A batch process to post the registration, to AR will subsequently need to be run., , If the registration post immediately flag is set to Yes,, this cutoff date determines which registration records, immediately affect AR.  Any registration whose billing, period start date is after this date will not affect, AR balances until a batch process is run to post unposted, registration charges to AR.  Any registration charges, whose billing period start date is on or before this date, will be posted to AR as soon as the record is saved., , If this is cutoff date is null and the registration post, immediately flag is set to Yes, then all registration, charges will post to AR regardless of date as soon as, the registration record is saved., , Defaults from AR.REG.POST.IMDTLY.DATE in AR.DEFAULTS, and can be changed.  If there is no value for the, location, the AR.DEFAULTS date will be used.

Yes/no flag specifying whether or not registration, charges and credits are to be posted to AR when they, are created.  No means that no reg postings records, and no invoices will be created when the student's, registration is created or updated; so the AR account, will not reflect the reg charges or credits until, a batch process runs to create the reg postings and, invoices.  The batch process creating the invoice, then updates the AR account., , If Yes then reg postings and invoice records may be, created immediately upon creating or updating a student's, registration depending upon the values of the billing, period start date of the registration and the billing, cutoff date (see LOC.AR.REG.POST.IMDTLY.DATE)., , Defaults from AR.REG.POST.IMDTLY.FLAG in AR.DEFAULTS, and can be changed.  If there is no value for the, location, the AR.DEFAULTS value is used.

This is the cutoff date for posting room charges, immediately to AR., , If the room post immediately flag is No, no room, charges hit AR when the room assignment is, created or a billing field on the room assignment, is maintained.  A batch process to post the room, assignments to AR will subsequently need to be run., , If the room post immediately flag is set to Yes,, this cutoff date determines which room assignments, immediately affect AR.  Any room assignment whose, billing period start date is after this date will, not affect AR balances until a batch process is, run to post unposted room assignments to AR.  Any, room assignment whose billing period start date is, on or before this date will be posted to AR as soon, as the record is saved., , If this cutoff date is null and the room post, immediately flag is set to Yes, then all room, assignments will post to AR regardless of date, as soon as the room assignment record is saved., , Defaults from AR.ROOM.POST.IMDTLY.DATE in, AR.DEFAULTS. The batch process creating the invoice, then updates the AR account., , If Yes then room postings and invoice records may be, created immediately upon creating or updating a room, assignment record depending upon the values of the, billing period start date of the room assignment and, the billing cutoff date (see LOC.AR.ROOM.POST.IMDTLY.DATE)., , Defaults from AR.ROOM.POST.IMDTLY.FLAG in AR.DEFAULTS, and can be changed. A batch process to, post the registration charges to AR will, subsequently need to be run., , If the section cancelation post immediately flag, is set to Yes, this cutoff date determines which, course section cancelations immediately affect AR., Any canceled course sections whose start date is, after this date will not affect AR balances until a, batch process is run to post registration charges, to AR.  When canceled, any course sections whose, start date is on or before this date may be posted, to AR immediately, depending on the end user's, actions (see LOC.SECCNCL.POST.IMDTLY.FLAG)., , If this cutoff date is null and the section, cancelation post immediately flag is set to Yes,, then all registration charges may be posted to AR,, regardless of date, as soon as the course section, is canceled., , Defaults from AR.SEC.CNCL.POST.IMDTLY.DATE in, AR.DEFAULTS and can be changed. The batch process creating the invoice, then updates the AR account., , If Yes then reg postings and invoice records may be, created immediately upon canceling a course section, depending upon the values of the billing period start, date of the registration and the billing cutoff date, (see LOC.SECCNCL.POST.IMDTLY.DATE)., , When canceling a course section through the course, section maintenance screen, if this flag is Yes and, the section start date is less than or equal to the, cutoff date, the user will be prompted whether or not, they want to bill immediately.  When canceling course, sections in batch, if this flag is Yes, the user will, be prompted on the front-end screen if they wish to, bill immediately.  If this flag is No, the user billing, will not be updated immediately in either scenario., , Defaults from AR.SEC.CNCL.POST.IMDTLY.FLAG in AR.DEFAULTS, and can be changed. However, that pointer, is on PERSON.ST, and most sponsors and parents and, anyone else paying for a student do not have PERSON.ST, records.  The rule processor is rejecting cases where, a record is not found.  To get around this, this, pointer is in PERSON, which then allows the rule to, evaluate with a null record if there is no PERSON.ST, record.  PERSON.ST is a cofile of PERSON., , SRM - 10/24/96, Rules processing no longer requires this field be, here since PST.RESTRICTIONS will not fail a rule when, the PERSON.ST record doesn't exist and simply return, a null list.

The lowest-level attribute stored to PLACES will always be , described by this PLACES.DESC attribute., For example, if a PLACES record contains 'AUS' in PLACES.COUNTRY and 'NSW' in , PLACES.REGION, and PLACES.SUB.REGION is blank, then the PLACES.DESC will store , the HEDM description "New South Wales" describing this region specific to , Australia., As another example, if the PLACES record contains 'AUS' in PLACES.COUNTRY, , 'NSW' in PLACES.REGION, and 'CC' in PLACES.SUB.REGION, then the PLACES.DESC , will store the HEDM description "Central Coast" describing this sub-region , specific to New South Wales, Australia.

Free-form text about relationship.  Displayed by not, otherwise used by the system.
Description of relationship. Shown on resolution, screens, and shown as relationship when GENDER is null.

Female role description, such as grandmother, mother, sister,, aunt, etc.  Blank for genderless relationships, such as, parent company, subsidiary, friend, etc.  This is used to, display the relationship for a female relation.  It will only, be used if the relation's gender is F (female).  Gender can be, entered on Name and Address Entry (NAE).
The translation to an enumeration within integration when a female is , identified with this relationship.
The translation to an enumeration within integration when a male is identified , with this relationship.
Translate to codes within an integration system.

The inverse of the relation type, which must also be in, this RELATION.TYPES file.  For example, for GP (grandparent),, this inverse is GC (grandchild); for PCO (parent company),, this might be SUB (subsidiary)., , This is used to determine the correct relationship to return, based on whose relationship is requested. A RELATION record, is keyed by two PERSON IDs (ID*ID).  The lesser (numerically), ID is always first.  The relation type is always of the first, ID.  This means that to look at the relationship of the second, ID from the first ID's point of view, the relationship to show, is the inverse., , For example, suppose ID 123 is the granddaughter of ID 234.  The, RELATION ID is 123*234.  The relation type on the RELATION record, is GC (or whatever means grandchild), since 123 is the lesser of, the two IDs.  On REL, if 123 is in context (in the header block),, then 234 shows in the Other group with a relation of Grandfather., We knew to show grandfather because GC has an inverse type of,, say, GP (grandparent), and the male description of that is, "Grandfather".  If 234 is in context, then 123 shows in the Other, group with a relation of Granddaughter.  In this case, the inverse, was not needed because the lesser ID would have its own relation, type on RELATION, and so for 123, the female description of GC,, "Granddaughter", is shown., , Many relationships do not have an inverse, such as spouse.  In, this case, the relation type is used for both IDs, using only, gender to distinguish, if male and female descriptions have, been provided.  If ID 123 is married to 345, and 345, has a gender of male, then if 123 is in context, then 345, would show as "Husband" if that was in the male relationship, description. If 345 is in context, 123 would show as "Wife" if, that was in the female relationship description.  If the male, and female description were left blank, then "Spouse" would show, for either.  If a relation did not have a gender, which would be, the case for organizations, then the relationship type description, shows, which should not denote a gender.

Male role description, such as grandfather, father, brother,, uncle, etc.  Blank for genderless relationships, such as, parent company, subsidiary, friend, etc.  This is used to, display the relationship for a male relation.  It will only, be used if the relation's gender is M (male).  Gender can be, entered on Name and Address Entry (NAE).

Yes/no flag to say if relationship is for organizations, only.  Y means only orgs, N means only people, null, means either.  Used to control entries of IDs in, relations.  For example, if this is Y (orgs only), then, this relationship cannot be entered for a person.
